image.altText: Funeral of Faraz Tahir

props.synopsis: The security guard who died trying to save shoppers from a knife attack at Bondi Junction Westfield is being remembered as a hero at funeral service in north west Sydney.

title.children: Faraz Tahir, security guard who tried to stop Bondi attacker, remembered as a national hero

image.altText: Emma Bates smiles, standing in front of a body of water under a sunny sky dotted with clouds.

props.synopsis: The accused, who police say was known to the victim, faces multiple assault charges in Shepparton Magistrates' Court over the death of Ms Bates, whose body was discovered in her Cobram home on Tuesday.

title.children: Cobram man faces court on assault charges following the death of Emma Bates

image.altText: A blue sleeve with a Victoria Police badge sewn into it, including the motto "Uphold the Right".

props.synopsis: A senior Victoria Police commander has issued a renewed call for family violence perpetrators to be put on a register in the same way as sex offenders. Her comments come as breaches of family violence intervention orders recorded by police more than doubled in a decade.

title.children: Police commander targets 'high-risk, prolific offenders' in family violence proposal

image.altText: Lights are on inside the Highpoint Shopping Centre, seen from outside under a red and blue morning sky.

props.synopsis: A 17-year-old boy has been charged after a stabbing during a brawl involving six people at Highpoint shopping centre. The incident follows a serious stabbing at the same shopping centre on Sunday.

title.children: Second stabbing at Melbourne shopping centre in less than a week

image.altText: GINA EDWARDS COURT

props.synopsis: Sydney barrister Gina Edwards has been awarded $150,000 in the Federal Court after bringing a defamation case against Network Nine over a series of stories that implied she had stolen her dog.

title.children: Sydney barrister awarded $150k in defamation damages over story about stolen dog

image.altText: A composite image of Peter FitSimons, wearing a red bandana, and Bruce Lehrmann in a suit and tie, wearing glasses.

props.synopsis: Former Liberal staffer Bruce Lehrmann is ordered to pay thousands of dollars to journalist Peter FitzSimons for costs incurred in Mr Lehrmann's failed defamation case.

title.children: Bruce Lehrmann agrees to pay more than $4,000 to journalist Peter FitzSimons to cover costs incurred during defamation trial

image.altText: A young man poses for a photo on a cliff face, with mountains behind him.

props.synopsis: Ben Cohen, who was falsely identified as the person behind the Bondi Junction stabbing attack by the Seven network, has settled his defamation case.

title.children: Man wrongly identified as Bondi Junction attacker by Seven settles defamation case with the network

image.altText: An aerial photo of a new housing estate with empty blocks and several new houses being built.

props.synopsis: There is mounting evidence that basic forms of insurance are becoming unaffordable for many Australians as the cost-of-living crisis deepens.

title.children: Households choosing food over insurance cover despite financial planners warning of big risks

image.altText: An older man in a beanie and spectacles, smiling warmly.

props.synopsis: A teenager kept his eyes lowered, occasionally glancing up at the screen, as footage of his deadly attack on a 75-year-old man was played to a court.

title.children: CCTV shows teen 'steeling' himself before fatal Toowoomba taxi rank attack

image.altText: A woman with brown hair and a blue shirt kneels with her two young daughters, who are both wearing pink

props.synopsis: Erin Paech's "gut just dropped" when she was told her north-west Victorian town of Hopetoun's only childcare centre would be closing after being unable to fill two vacant qualified educator roles.

title.children: 'Quit my job or move to Melbourne': Families face confronting choices as childcare hub shuts

image.altText: A child's hand written card saying 'dear mum, I think you are great'.

props.synopsis: A social worker at a child contact centre has alleged key players in a family court case ignored her concerns about the possible abuse of a four-year-old girl.

title.children: Joan told her manager at a child contact centre she was worried 4yo Sally might be being abused. She was later fired

image.altText: Four CCTV panels of a woman walkign through the door of a shop in a coat carrying a bag

props.synopsis: Journalist Jill Dando was at the height of her career and preparing for a fast-approaching wedding when she was murdered in 1999. Now 25 years later, there are still unanswered questions.

title.children: One of the BBC's most popular presenters was 'assassinated on her doorstep in broad daylight' more than two decades ago

image.altText: A picture of a vial of liquid labelled as 'hydromorphone'.

props.synopsis: The Victorian government has walked away from plans to create a second supervised injecting room in Melbourne. But buried in the announcement were plans to trial a powerful painkiller used to help heroin kick the habit. Is it a sufficient alternative?

title.children: This drug has been used for years to help people kick addiction in Canada. Now Victoria's giving it a go

image.altText: Jenny Macklin

props.synopsis: An expert panel tasked with advising the federal government on income supports says the JobSeeker unemployment payment must be increased by about $17 a day as a "first priority" in next month's budget, arguing any move would have a "negligible" inflationary impact.

title.children: Government told JobSeeker increase of $17 a day would have minimal inflation impact

image.altText: a zoomed in woolworths sign

props.synopsis: A Melbourne magistrate has described a Woolworths payroll error as a systematic and gross failure, but says the company is remorseful.

title.children: Woolworths fined $1.2 million over 'gross failure' to pay Victorian staff entitlements

image.altText: A busy pedestrian crossing at the intersection of Spencer and Collins streets in Melbourne's CBD.

props.synopsis: Data from the OECD shows Australia recorded the biggest increase to average tax rates in the developed world last year due to bracket creep and the end of a tax offset, but a separate report finds Australia is still a relatively low-taxing nation.

title.children: Australians had the biggest income tax increase in the developed world last year but we're not the most-taxed country, finds OECD

image.altText: Missing woman Jessica Zrinski smiling while sat in a car

props.synopsis: The NSW Homicide Squad begins a second search for missing Sydney woman Jessica Zrinski around the Jenolan Caves area in the NSW Central Tablelands.

title.children: Homicide detectives scour Jenolan Caves bushland for signs of missing woman Jessica Zrinski

image.altText: Joal Presincula leaning against a brick wall.

props.synopsis: When Joal was homeless as a child no-one bothered to ask her how she was feeling or what she needed. She now advocates for children going through a similar experience.

title.children: 'I just had no idea what was going on': Joal was five when she experienced homelessness for the first time

image.altText: Cutouts of two Aboriginal girls over a picture of an empty road in the desert.

props.synopsis: On a road out the back of Bourke, the lives of two Indigenous teenage girls ended in 1987. They were failed by the police as the lawyer for the defendant played on racial tensions in the town.

title.children: ‘Predatory and disgraceful’: The man who plied teens with alcohol before doing the unthinkable

image.altText: Joel Embiid pictured during the NBA playoffs

props.synopsis: Philadelphia 76ers star Joel Embiid went to the doctors complaining of a migraine prior to the playoffs, only for the diagnosis to be something more sinister that impacts how he looks on the court.

title.children: 'Thought it was nothing': NBA star reveals battle with rare facial paralysis condition

image.altText: Harvey Weinstein dressed in a suit, sitting in a court room

props.synopsis: The ruling by a New York high court has been called a major step back for survivors of sexual abuse, with some fearing it could deter other victims from coming forward in similar cases.

title.children: Rose McGowan, Ashley Judd and #MeToo founder react to the overturning of Harvey Weinstein's rape conviction

image.altText: A group of Muslim leaders gather together in a line in a park

props.synopsis: Three of Australia's peak Islamic groups have called for a revision of terrorism laws and a review into Wednesday's counterterrorism raids.

title.children: Peak Islamic groups call for review of Sydney counterterrorism raids that led to five teenagers charged

image.altText: A man walks next to a girl who stares at him adoringly with a hand on his chest

props.synopsis: The elevation of Kim Jong Un's female relatives coincides with the growing economic and social power of women living inside secretive North Korea.

title.children: 'You have to be agile and pivot': Kim keeps showing off his daughter — and it may be for his own survival

image.altText: Three protesters in masks

props.synopsis: Almost every week in US politics is action-packed. This one featured Trump grumbling about the aircon in court and Biden under pressure as campus tensions spiral, writes Jade Macmillan.

title.children: A chilly, grumpy Trump and Biden's growing youth vote problem: This week in US politics

image.altText: An orange BHP logo on a grey background.

props.synopsis: The ASX has ended lower on Friday, while Anglo American has rejected BHP's $60 billion takeover bid, saying it "undervalues" the British mining company and its future prospects.

title.children: Anglo American rejects BHP $60b takeover offer, saying it 'significantly undervalues' the mining company — as it happened

image.altText: David Lambourne airport

props.synopsis: An Australian judge is a step closer to being deported from Kiribati after the country's parliament voted in favour of his removal from the High Court.

title.children: Australian-born judge David Lambourne closer to deportation from Kiribati

image.altText: close up of side of Scott Morrison's face

props.synopsis: Former prime minister Scott Morrison reveals his experiences with acute anxiety while serving as the nation's leader, saying it is a conversation that should be normalised in federal politics.

title.children: Scott Morrison says he took medication for anxiety as prime minister

image.altText: A woman hugs a man from behind.

props.synopsis: Social services advocates call for basic safety standards to be introduced for temporary accommodation as people "at their most desperate" are forced to accept unsafe housing options.

title.children: Homeless couple say no locks on doors, broken fire alarms in short-term housing, put lives at risk

image.altText: Grey-headed Flying Fox mother and pup with distinctive ruff around neck and chest.

props.synopsis: Grey-headed flying foxes move into new locations in search of food and habitat, and their defenders say residents need to learn to live with the sometimes noisy and smelly creatures.

title.children: Flying foxes are coming to a town near you, and experts say we need to learn to live with them

image.altText: Image of two saddled horses, one black, one white, running through the street. The white horse has blood on its hooves.

props.synopsis: Two military horses that bolted through the streets of London after being spooked by construction noise are in serious condition after undergoing surgery.

title.children: Two military horses that broke free and ran loose across London have undergone surgery

image.altText: Former US President Donald Trump looks on inside a New York courtroom.

props.synopsis: Former National Enquirer publisher David Pecker testifies at Donald Trump's criminal trial that he wrangled with Mr Trump and his former lawyer ahead of the 2016 election over who should buy the silence of women who said they had sexual encounters with him.

title.children: National Enquirer publisher says he wrangled with Donald Trump over who should buy sex stories

image.altText: two brumbies walking along in long grass within a national park

props.synopsis: The program will be halted pending an investigation after hundreds of horse carcasses, including brumbies, were allegedly found on a property near Wagga Wagga.

title.children: NSW suspends brumby rehoming after discovery of hundreds of dead horses

image.altText: Ryan Gosling in aviator sunglasses and a sleeveless vest leans an arm against a doorframe

props.synopsis: Ryan Gosling and Emily Blunt star in an action movie that's also an ode to the art of filmmaking, a musical nostalgia-fest, and a love story.

title.children: Ryan Gosling brings comedy and charm to stunt-filled, high-octane romance The Fall Guy
